Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:42 pm - Defendant Spencer M. Gulseth in court.  Attorney Nathan J. Heim in court for Spencer M. Gulseth.  Prosecuting attorney Jordan W. Feest appeared by video for the State of Wisconsin. Defendant waives their right to a preliminary hearing.  Defendant is bound over to Circuit Court Branch 2 for trial. Email inducement dated 08-18-22.

Information filed.  Copy served on defense counsel.
Not guilty plea(s) entered.  Jury calendar.
Further proceedings scheduled for September 30, 2022 at 08:30 am.

Defendant demands a preliminary hearing.   Preliminary hearing is set for 08-24-22 at 1:30 p.m.    
Minutes.

Initial appearance is reset to 08-15-22 at 1:30 p.m. to allow the public defender more time to appoint counsel.   
Minutes.
Re:  Threatening to communicate derogatory information, on 06-16-22.
Order to report to MTPD for photo and prints

BAIL HEARING - 
Defendant in custody and appearing by video from the Manitowoc County Jail.  The State informs the Court that the defendant will be charged with the crime of threats to communicate derogatory information.  The matter is continued for initial appearance on 07-18-22 at 1:30 p.m.  Bail is set at $2,000.00 recognizance bond with the conditions that he report to the Manitowoc City Police Department for fingerprints, photographs and identifying information within 48 hours or, if incarcerated, within 72 hours of release and defendant is to have no contact with S.T.W. DOB: 10-09-93 or any premises he may occupy.  Bail furnished and defendant is released from custody.
